  "text": "In human erythrocytes, GST is present in large amounts (5 ) and in two forms: a highly cationic enzyme (designated with the Greek letter ), which accounts for Ͻ5% of the total GST activity; and the main anionic enzyme corresponding to the P form () [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Because of its abundance and overlapping substrate specificity with the form, the GST P1-1 dimer is often considered the sole GST enzyme in the erythrocyte [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] .",
